{
  "answer": "In the *Bṛhaspati Smṛti*, writing—rendered in the translation as \"document\" (*lekhya* in Sanskrit)—is treated as a primary form of human proof (*mānusa pramāṇa*) in legal disputes, alongside witnesses and possession (or inference). It takes precedence over divine ordeals (e.g., fire or water tests) when available: \"Divine proof is not prescribed when witnesses are available; and when a document exists in disputes, there should be neither an ordeal nor witnesses.\"[^1]\n\nDocuments are one of three kinds of human proof, further subdivided into eight types, and litigants must substantiate claims with them when applicable.[^2] An entire subsection (1.6) is devoted to rules governing documents, including their required contents (e.g., date, place, parties, transaction details, and witnesses' subscriptions).[^3]\n\n[^1]: *Bṛhaspati Smṛti*, ch. 1, [p-44a57a](/works/unknown-brhaspati-smrti-0fd070/01/translation/#p-44a57a).\n\n[^2]: *Bṛhaspati Smṛti*, ch. 1, [p-510297](/works/unknown-brhaspati-smrti-0fd070/01/translation/#p-510297), [p-c9cb41](/works/unknown-brhaspati-smrti-0fd070/01/translation/#p-c9cb41), and [p-cce2d2](/works/unknown-brhaspati-smrti-0fd070/01/translation/#p-cce2d2).\n\n[^3]: *Bṛhaspati Smṛti*, ch. 1, [p-f172b3](/works/unknown-brhaspati-smrti-0fd070/01/translation/#p-f172b3) and [p-bbce9d](/works/unknown-brhaspati-smrti-0fd070/01/translation/#p-bbce9d).",
